s.\n5. Incorporating factorials for unique scoring (but remember to import math).\n6. Using conditional logic to adjust priorities based on bin states.\n7. Applying element-wise operations with broadcasting.\n8. Using trigonometric functions in combination with other operations.\n9. Creating composite functions by combining multiple mathematical operations.\n10. Experimenting with different scaling factors.\n\n### Final Instructions:\n- Write each function as a separate code block.\n- Ensure that each function is unique and meets all the requirements.\n- Avoid any code that would make the function non-vectorized or inefficient.\n\n### Deliverable:\n- 10 unique implementations of the priority function.\n\n### Example Output:\n\n```\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n```\n\n### Final Note:\nMake sure that each function is correct and unique. Each function should not be a copy of another but should use a different combination of operations.\n</think>\n\n```\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n```\n\n```\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.std(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n```\n\n```\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n```\n\n```\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n```\n\n```\ndef priority(item: f